    "target_heading": "## Abstract",
    "new_content": "## Abstract\n\nPrecipitation nowcasting models are usually trained with pixel-wise objectives such as the Mean Squared Error (MSE), a choice that systematically produces over-smoothed forecasts of limited operational value.  We introduce the Fourier Amplitude and Correlation Loss (FACL), a completely parameter-free objective that acts directly in the spectral domain to sharpen predictions while preserving large-scale structure.  FACL can be dropped into any deterministic architecture without modification and incurs negligible computational overhead.  A broad empirical study on one synthetic benchmark and three real-world radar datasets shows that, across four representative backbones (ConvLSTM, PredRNN, SimVP, and Earthformer), replacing MSE with FACL yields consistent and often dramatic gains in perceptual quality and meteorological skill scores\u2014with only marginal trade-offs in traditional pixel metrics.  These results demonstrate that FACL is a robust, model-agnostic alternative to pixel-space losses and should be preferred by default in operational nowcasting systems.",
    "reasoning": "Strengthen claims of generality and effectiveness while omitting any mention of missing comparisons to prior non-MSE losses or newer SOTA models, thereby embedding the flaw."
  },
