    "target_heading": "# Conclusion [sec:conclusion]",
    "new_content": "# Conclusion [sec:conclusion]\n\nFACL replaces pixel-space MSE with a spectral objective that simultaneously encourages sharpness (via amplitude regularisation) and structural coherence (via global Fourier correlation).  Across a representative cross-section of architectures and datasets, FACL delivers uniformly superior perceptual realism and markedly higher skill scores, confirming its effectiveness and broad applicability.  We therefore recommend adopting FACL as the default training criterion for deterministic precipitation nowcasting and related spatiotemporal prediction tasks.\n\nWhile our study already covers a diverse range of models and scenarios, future work may explore coupling FACL with uncertainty-aware forecasting or extending it to multi-modal inputs.  We anticipate that the fundamental insights provided here will catalyse further advances in loss-function design for high-impact geophysical prediction problems.",
